      "content": "Absolutely, the heat is the primary trigger for the Maillard reaction, but other factors significantly influence it. Moisture and pH play crucial roles—lower moisture levels increases reaction rates, and acidic conditions can ramp up it even more. When bread bakes, the heat causes sugars and proteins to react, forming flavorful compounds. Yeast and enzymatic activity initially cause sugars to form, but it's the Maillard reaction enhanced by oven temperatures that truly gives rise to the aroma and crust of an excellent loaf of bread. Understanding these factors allows you to control the results, bringing out the \"magic\" in your baking.",
